#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Fill mkt-original gaps in 1 Chronicles 21–22 (46 missing verses).
Existing: ch21 vv1,22; ch22 v9. Covers census/plague/threshing-floor and temple-prep charge.
Key interpretive decisions:
  - śāṭān (21:1) vs. YHWH (2 Sam 24:1): the Chronicler refines anthropomorphic language;
    Satan is a heavenly adversary functioning within YHWH's sovereign permission (cf. Job 1–2)
  - 600 shekels gold (21:25) vs. 50 silver (2 Sam 24:24): Chronicles buys the entire temple
    site; Samuel buys only the threshing floor — different transactions, not a contradiction
  - Fire from heaven (21:26): divine confirmation matching Lev 9:24 and 2 Chr 7:1
  - šᵉlōmōh / šālôm wordplay explicit in 22:9: Solomon as typological sabbath-king
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / f"data/commentary/{layer}/{book}.json"
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / f"data/commentary/{layer}/{book}.json"
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON = {
"21": {
"2": "<p><span class='term'>śᵉʾû</span> (\"count, muster\") is the census verb; <span class='term'>mibᵉʾēr šebaʿ ʿad-dān</span> (\"from Beersheba to Dan\") reverses the conventional south-to-north idiom — the Chronicler writes from a Jerusalem-centered perspective rather than the northern vantage of the Deuteronomistic History. Joab and the \"army commanders\" (<span class='term'>śārê hāʿām</span>) are the census agents; the military framing reveals David's purpose — this is a war-preparation census rather than a Mosaic cultic numbering.</p>",
"3": "<p>Joab's objection deploys a formal wish-formula: <span class='term'>yôsep YHWH ʿal-ʿammô meʾâ pᵉʿāmîm</span> (\"may YHWH add to his people a hundredfold\") — prayer and protest simultaneously. The rhetorical question <span class='term'>ʾăḏōnî hammelek ʾăḥîhem</span> (\"are they not all, my lord the king, his servants?\") frames the census as a category error: YHWH's people cannot be numbered as a military asset. The verb <span class='term'>ʾāšām</span> (incur guilt) at the end carries full legal weight — Joab predicts cultic violation, not just political miscalculation.</p>",
"4": "<p><span class='term'>wayyiḥzaq dᵉḇar-hammelek ʿal-yôʾāḇ</span> — \"the king's word prevailed over Joab\" — the verb <span class='term'>ḥzq</span> (be strong, overpower) signals inappropriate coercion. David's royal command overrides prophetic-priestly caution; this is the Chronicler's structural explanation for why discipline followed: leadership failed to heed legitimate counsel. <span class='term'>wayyēleḵ yôʾāḇ wayᵉhî bᵉḵol-yiśrāʾēl wayyāšāḇ yᵉrûšālim</span> — the census circuit encompassed all Israel before reporting back, suggesting weeks of travel.</p>",
"5": "<p>The numbers differ significantly from 2 Sam 24:9 (800,000 Israel / 500,000 Judah vs. 1,100,000 / 470,000 here). Chronicles' higher Israel figure may reflect a different counting methodology (including military reserves or all eligible males), or may preserve a variant source. The Chronicler does not harmonize the discrepancy; both texts stand in the canon as complementary witnesses. <span class='term'>šōlēp ḥereḇ</span> (\"able to wield a sword\") confirms the military census framing — this is warrior-counting, not Mosaic covenant numbering.</p>",
"6": "<p>Levi and Benjamin's exclusion from the census is the Chronicler's addition to the Samuel parallel. <span class='term'>wᵉlēwî wᵉḇinyāmîn lōʾ pāqad bᵉtôḵām</span> — Levi was never numbered in Mosaic censuses (Num 1:49; 2:33); Benjamin's exclusion may reflect the fact that the future temple site at Ornan's threshing floor lay within Benjamin's tribal territory (Josh 18:28), making Benjamin's people the custodians of sacred space rather than military conscripts. Joab's act of mercy toward these two tribes foreshadows the temple-centered restoration of both.</p>",
"7": "<p><span class='term'>wayyēraʿ bᵉʿênê hāʾĕlōhîm</span> — \"it was evil/displeasing in the eyes of God.\" The narrator's use of generic <span class='term'>hāʾĕlōhîm</span> here rather than the covenant name YHWH may mark this as a straightforward moral evaluation before the personal covenant dimension emerges in God's disciplinary response. <span class='term'>wayyak ʾet-yiśrāʾēl</span> — \"he struck Israel\" — the collective punishment falls on the people David numbered, not only on David. Covenantal solidarity means the nation bears the consequence of its leader's hubris.</p>",
"8": "<p>David's confession: <span class='term'>ḥāṭāʾtî mᵉʾōd</span> (\"I have sinned greatly\") uses the intensifying adverb <span class='term'>mᵉʾōd</span> to mark the gravity of the admission. The petition <span class='term'>haʿăḇēr nāʾ ʾet-ʿăwōn ʿaḇdᵉḵā</span> uses <span class='term'>ʿāḇar</span> (\"cause to pass over\") for forgiveness — a spatial metaphor for removing guilt from one's account. <span class='term'>kiskalatî mᵉʾōd</span> — \"I have acted very foolishly\" — <span class='term'>sāḵal</span> refers to foolishness that causes harm, the wisdom-tradition antonym of understanding. David recognizes his failure as both moral sin and practical folly.</p>",
"9": "<p><span class='term'>waydabber YHWH ʾel-gāḏ ḥōzeh dāwîd</span> — YHWH speaks directly to Gad, whom the Chronicler titles <span class='term'>ḥōzeh dāwîd</span> (\"David's seer\"), using the visionary prophet title (<span class='term'>ḥōzeh</span>) rather than the more common <span class='term'>nāḇîʾ</span>. The seer tradition (cf. 1 Sam 9:9) emphasizes visual revelation; Gad is the prophet whose role is to mediate YHWH's vision for what David cannot directly see. <span class='term'>lēʾmōr</span> (\"saying\") introduces the divine word that Gad must transmit — YHWH → Gad → David is the complete prophetic chain that governs the chapter's disciplinary structure.</p>",
"10": "<p>YHWH's three-choice oracle delivered through Gad (<span class='term'>ḥōzeh dāwîd</span> — \"David's seer\") exemplifies the prophetic intermediary role in Chronicles: YHWH communicates discipline options rather than simply imposing punishment unilaterally. The phrase <span class='term'>šālaš ʾānī nōṭeh ʿāleḵā</span> (\"I am stretching/extending three things toward you\") — <span class='term'>nāṭâ</span> describes both extending a hand in offer and extending a hand in punishment, creating a deliberate ambiguity: choosing is itself an act within God's sovereign frame.</p>",
"11": "<p>Gad's enumeration begins with <span class='term'>bāḥar-lᵉḵā ʾaḥat mēhem</span> — \"choose one of them for yourself\" — the language of personal selection. The three options — famine, military defeat, plague — correspond precisely to the covenant curse triad of Deut 28 and Lev 26 (sword, famine, pestilence), though reversed in order. The census sin against the covenant people is answered by covenant-curse options; discipline fits the offense structurally.</p>",
"12": "<p><span class='term'>šāloš šānîm rāʿāb</span> (three years famine) / <span class='term'>šᵉlōšâ ḥŏdāšîm</span> (three months before enemies' sword) / <span class='term'>šᵉlōšet yāmîm ḥereḇ YHWH wᵉdeḇer</span> (three days YHWH's sword and plague) — the three options scale inversely: more human control (famine, long but survivable) → less human control (war, determined by enemies) → no human control (divine plague, the briefest but most total). The interplay of timescales creates a theology of divine initiative: YHWH's direct hand moves fastest and most decisively.</p>",
"13": "<p>David's response is the theological heart of the chapter: <span class='term'>naple nāʾ bᵉyad-YHWH kî-raḇbîm raḥămāyw</span> — \"let me fall into YHWH's hand, for his mercies are great.\" <span class='term'>raḥămîm</span> (mercies, plural of intensity) is the compassion-word rooted in <span class='term'>reḥem</span> (womb) — YHWH's mercies are maternal, tender, and abundant. The opposite refusal — <span class='term'>ûḇᵉyad-ʾādām ʾal-ʾeppōl</span> (\"but let me not fall into human hands\") — reflects the wisdom that human enemies show less mercy than the God whose character is defined by covenant faithfulness (<span class='term'>ḥesed</span> and <span class='term'>raḥămîm</span>).</p>",
"14": "<p><span class='term'>wayyittēn YHWH deḇer bᵉyiśrāʾēl</span> — the plague falls immediately and directly. <span class='term'>šiḇʿîm ʾelep ʾîš</span> (seventy thousand men) — precisely those counted in the census die, an ironic fulfillment of Joab's warning. The act of counting them for military purposes ends with those counted removed from Israel's military potential. The Chronicler's narrative insists that national strength flows from covenant fidelity, not demographic calculation.</p>",
"15": "<p>The theophany at Jerusalem is one of Chronicles' most dramatic scenes: <span class='term'>wayyišlaḥ hāʾĕlōhîm malʾāḵ lîrûšālim lᵉšaḥătāh</span> — God sends an angel to destroy Jerusalem. Then the pivot: <span class='term'>wayyinnāḥem YHWH ʿal-hārāʿâ</span> — YHWH relented/repented of the disaster; <span class='term'>nāḥam</span> is the strongest anthropomorphic term for divine change of emotional state. The command <span class='term'>rab-lāk ʿᵊtāh haref yādᵉḵā</span> (\"Enough! Now stay your hand\") is spoken by YHWH directly to the angel — a command within the divine council that reverses the destruction. The threshing floor of Ornan the Jebusite is identified as the site where the angel stands.</p>",
"16": "<p><span class='term'>wayyiśśāʾ dāwîd ʾet-ʿênāyw wayyarᵉʾ ʾet-malʾak YHWH ʿōmēd bên hāʾāreṣ ûḇên haššāmayim wᵉḥarḇô šᵉlûpâ bᵉyādô</span> — David sees the angel standing between earth and heaven, sword drawn, extended over Jerusalem. The spatial positioning — between spheres — marks the angel as a liminal figure operating at the intersection of divine and human realms. David and the elders respond with full covenant penitence: <span class='term'>wayyipᵉlû ʿal-pᵉnêhem</span> (fell on their faces) in <span class='term'>śaqqîm</span> (sackcloth) — the full mourning posture.</p>",
"17": "<p>David's second confession explicitly inverts the guilt structure: <span class='term'>ʾănî hûʾ ʾăšer ḥāṭāʾtî wᵉhārēaʿ hārēʿōtî</span> — \"I am the one who sinned and acted wickedly\" — <span class='term'>hārēʿōtî</span> is infinitive absolute + perfect for emphatic confirmation of guilt. The contrast <span class='term'>hāʾēlleh haṣṣōʾn mah ʿāśû</span> (\"these sheep — what have they done?\") employs the shepherding metaphor (David as shepherd-king) to argue for redirecting punishment from people to king. The petition <span class='term'>ûbi-yādᵉḵā tihi-nāʾ ʾet-yādᵉḵā bî</span> — \"let your hand be against me and my father's house\" — offers self and dynastic substitution for the people's suffering.</p>",
"18": "<p>The angel's instruction to Gad demonstrates the Chronicler's chain-of-command theology: YHWH → angel → prophet → king; <span class='term'>yaʿal dāwîd lᵉhāqîm mizbēaḥ lYHWH</span> (\"David is to go up to build an altar to YHWH\") transforms the site of the plague's arrest into the site of permanent sacrifice. The threshing floor (<span class='term'>gōren ʾornān hayᵉḇûsî</span>) is a liminal space — where harvest grain is separated from chaff — that becomes the dividing line between destruction and mercy, between the old Jebusite past and the Israelite sacred future.</p>",
"19": "<p><span class='term'>wayyaʿal dāwîd biḏḇar-gāḏ ʾăšer dibber bᵉšem YHWH</span> — \"David went up in obedience to Gad's word, spoken in YHWH's name.\" The Chronicler's notation that the prophetic word was \"spoken in YHWH's name\" (<span class='term'>bᵉšem YHWH</span>) is a technical phrase for validated prophecy (cf. Deut 18:20–22). David's immediate obedience after his confession contrasts sharply with the fatal hesitation of the census — repentance here is demonstrated by action, not merely expressed in words.</p>",
"20": "<p><span class='term'>wayyiphen ʾornān wayyarᵉʾ ʾet-hammalʾāḵ</span> — Ornan turned and saw the angel; the verb <span class='term'>pānâ</span> (turn around) implies he was working with his back to the city when the angel appeared over Jerusalem. <span class='term'>wᵉʾarḇaʿat bānāyw ʿimmô yitḥabbᵉʾû</span> — \"his four sons who were with him hid themselves\" — <span class='term'>ḥāḇāʾ</span> (hide, take cover) reflects the instinctive theophanic fear response; ordinary humans conceal themselves before divine manifestations (cf. Exod 3:6, Moses hides his face; 1 Kgs 19:13, Elijah wraps his face). Ornan himself did not hide — he remained at his post, the owner of the site where heaven and earth were intersecting. The contrast between the hiding sons and the standing father sets up Ornan's composed response when David arrives in v21.</p>",
"21": "<p>The meeting of David and Ornan has formal protocols: Ornan saw David coming, emerged from the threshing floor (<span class='term'>mitten-haggōren</span>), and prostrated himself face-down (<span class='term'>wayyištaḥû lᵉdāwîd ʾappayim ʾārᵉṣâ</span>). The double gesture — exit from the floor + full prostration — marks the transfer of sacred space authority from the current occupant to the divinely-designated purchaser. Ornan's role as a Jebusite (a non-Israelite) who held the site that would become the temple mount is a subtle theological statement: YHWH's purposes can be served through any people's land transactions.</p>",
"23": "<p>Ornan's extraordinary generosity — oxen for burnt offering, threshing sledges for wood, wheat for grain offering — offers to supply everything David needs for free. <span class='term'>hakōl nātattî</span> (\"all of it I give\") is emphatic. The verb <span class='term'>nātan</span> (give) signals the gift economy that Ornan proposes; David's counter-refusal (<span class='term'>lōʾ-ʾeqqaḥ</span> in v24) establishes the purchase economy as the only valid basis for worship. The theological principle is explicit: YHWH's altar cannot be built on someone else's generosity — the worshiper must personally bear the cost.</p>",
"24": "<p>David's foundational statement: <span class='term'>lōʾ-ʾeqqaḥ ʾăšer-lᵉḵā lYHWH wᵉhaʿălôt ʿōlôt ḥinnām</span> — \"I will not take what is yours for YHWH, or offer burnt offerings that cost me nothing.\" The word <span class='term'>ḥinnām</span> (\"for free, at no cost\") is the key term; it appears in prophetic indictments of meaningless worship (Mal 1:10) and here establishes that genuine worship requires genuine sacrifice. This principle governs the entire temple-building enterprise: David's preparations (ch22), Solomon's labor, the people's freewill offerings (1 Chr 29) — none of it is costless generosity; all of it is chosen sacrifice.</p>",
"25": "<p><span class='term'>šēš-mēʾôt šeqel zāhāb miśqāl</span> — six hundred shekels of gold by weight. The 2 Sam 24:24 parallel records fifty shekels of silver for the threshing floor and oxen alone; the Chronicles figure reflects purchase of the full temple site (a much larger area) and is thus not contradictory. Gold rather than silver signals the purchase's sacred significance — this is not a normal real-estate transaction but the acquisition of holy ground. The payment establishes legal title that no future Jebusite claim could challenge.</p>",
"26": "<p>The divine response is unambiguous: <span class='term'>wayyanswheû bāʾēš min-haššāmayim ʿal mizbah hāʿōlâ</span> — \"he answered him with fire from heaven on the altar of burnt offering.\" Fire from heaven is the sign of divine acceptance in the three great sanctuary inauguration moments: Moses' tabernacle (Lev 9:24), David's altar here, and Solomon's temple (2 Chr 7:1). The Chronicler deliberately echoes all three, constructing a theological chain: one divine fire, three sacred sites, one continuous story of YHWH dwelling with his people. The angel's sword sheathes in the same verse as the fire falls — destruction gives way to acceptance.</p>",
"27": "<p><span class='term'>wayyōʾmer YHWH lammalʾāḵ wayyāšeḇ ḥarbô ʾel-nādānāhh</span> — \"the LORD commanded the angel, and he returned his sword to its sheath.\" The sheathing of the drawn sword (<span class='term'>ḥereḇ šᵉlûpâ</span>) that appeared in v16 creates a narrative bracket: plague began with drawn sword / ends with sheathed sword. The altar's dedication simultaneously ends the plague and establishes the permanent cult site — one act accomplishes two things: communal reconciliation with YHWH and the identification of the holy place.</p>",
"28": "<p>The summary statement locates David's sacrifice at the Ornan threshing floor as a direct response to divine answer: <span class='term'>kî rāʾâ kî-ʿānāhû YHWH bᵉgōren ʾornān hayᵉḇûsî</span> — \"because he saw that YHWH had answered him there.\" The theology is spatial: YHWH answered at this specific site, marking it as the locus of effective intercession. The threshing floor is no longer Ornan's economic space but YHWH's answer-site. Sacrifice at this location will henceforth be the normative response to YHWH's self-disclosure.</p>",
"29": "<p>The parenthetical note about the tabernacle at Gibeon (<span class='term'>ûmiškan YHWH ʾăšer-ʿāśâ mōšeh bammidbār wᵉmizbah hāʿōlâ bāʿēt hahîʾ bāmâ bᵉgiḇʿôn</span>) serves a critical theological function: it explains why David could not simply go to the legitimate Mosaic worship center. The tabernacle and its altar were the authorized cult site, but the angel's presence at Jerusalem made that the effective worship location. The Chronicler is navigating a genuine liturgical tension — the legal center (Gibeon) vs. the providentially designated center (Jerusalem) — that will only be resolved when Solomon builds the temple and brings the ark and tabernacle furnishings together.</p>",
"30": "<p><span class='term'>wᵉlōʾ-yāḵōl dāwîd lāleḵet lᵉḏārōš ʾĕlōhîm kî nibhal mippᵉnê ḥereḇ malʾak YHWH</span> — \"David could not go there to seek God because he was terrified before the sword of the angel of YHWH.\" <span class='term'>nāḇal/bāhal</span> (terrified, alarmed) captures genuine theophanic fear, not cowardice. The verse functions as the transition logic: David's inability to use the Mosaic altar at Gibeon is not disobedience but divine redirection. YHWH has effectively relocated authorized worship to the Jerusalem site through the theophany itself — the temple is built where divine fire fell and divine terror prevented departure.</p>",
},
"22": {
"1": "<p><span class='term'>wayyōʾmer dāwîd zeh hûʾ bêt YHWH hāʾĕlōhîm wᵉzeh-mizbēaḥ lᵉʿōlâ lᵉyiśrāʾēl</span> — David's declaratory sentence is the theological hinge of Chronicles. The demonstrative <span class='term'>zeh</span> (\"this\") is repeated: this place / this altar — a performative speech-act designating sacred geography. The threshing floor where fire fell and the sword sheathed is now officially identified as the permanent temple site and national altar. David does not ask for divine confirmation; the theophany of ch21 was itself the designation. He interprets the events with prophetic authority.</p>",
"2": "<p><span class='term'>gērîm</span> (resident aliens, sojourners) were the labor pool conscripted for stone preparation. The Mosaic law protected <span class='term'>gērîm</span> from exploitation but did not prohibit their employment in public works; the Chronicler's matter-of-fact note about their assembly reflects the Persian-period reality that the Jerusalem temple community included non-Israelite workers integrated into the economic and social fabric of Yehud. David's procurement policy here parallels Solomon's later corvée labor organization (2 Chr 2:17–18), demonstrating planned consistency across the two reigns.</p>",
"3": "<p><span class='term'>barzel lārōḇ lammismerôt daltôt haššᵉʿārîm wᵉlammaḥbᵉrôt</span> — iron in great quantity for door-nails and joints; <span class='term'>nᵉḥōšet lᵉʾên mišqāl</span> — bronze beyond weighing. The enumeration of materials (iron/bronze/cedar/stone) follows the ANE royal building-account convention visible in Mesopotamian inscriptions where kings catalog their procurement to demonstrate both divine favor (abundance) and royal diligence (preparation). David's stockpiling occurs during his reign but is designated entirely for Solomon — an act of dynastic stewardship rather than personal glory.</p>",
"4": "<p>Cedar from Sidon and Tyre was the prestige building material of the ancient Levant, unavailable in Israel's highlands. The Phoenician trade relationship established here by David (and formalized by Solomon with Hiram of Tyre in 2 Chr 2) reflects the economic reality that Israel's hill-country ecology could not supply the temple's architectural needs. The Chronicler's inclusion of this detail grounds the sacred project in practical geopolitics: the temple required international trade partnerships that transcended Israel's borders, foreshadowing its role as a house for all peoples.</p>",
"5": "<p>David's explanation for his preparations is simultaneously humble and visionary: <span class='term'>šᵉlōmōh bᵉnî naʿar wārāk</span> (\"my son Solomon is young and inexperienced/tender\") — <span class='term'>rāk</span> means soft/gentle, sometimes with the nuance of vulnerability; <span class='term'>naʿar</span> marks life stage, not inability. The temple must be <span class='term'>lᵉgādôl lᵉšēm wᵉlᵉtipʾeret lᵉḵol-hāʾărāṣôt</span> — \"magnificent in fame and glory to all lands\" — a universal visibility claim. David's preparations are a form of protective provision: he removes the logistical burden from Solomon's shoulders so that the young king can focus on the spiritual dimensions of the task.</p>",
"6": "<p>David's personal charge to Solomon begins with <span class='term'>wayyiqrāʾ lišlōmōh bᵉnô</span> — \"he called his son Solomon\" — an intimate summons preceding the formal commission. The content of the charge (vv7–16) follows the structure of a testamentary address: historical retrospective (vv7–8) → promise citation (vv9–10) → blessing (vv11) → conditional exhortation (vv12–13) → resource inventory (vv14–16). This is David's spiritual will, not merely a building brief.</p>",
"7": "<p><span class='term'>hayyâ ʿim-lᵉḇāḇî liḇnôt bêt lᵉšēm YHWH ʾĕlōhāy</span> — \"it was in my heart to build a house for the name of YHWH my God.\" <span class='term'>hayyâ ʿim-lᵉḇāḇî</span> (\"was with my heart\") is the Chronicler's idiom for sincere personal desire (cf. 1 Kgs 8:17, Solomon's retrospective). Intention matters in Chronicles — David's failed intention is not erased by its non-fulfillment; it is honored by YHWH's alternative arrangement. The house \"for the name\" (<span class='term'>lᵉšēm</span>) reflects the Name Theology of Deuteronomy: YHWH's presence is mediated through his name dwelling in a designated place, not through physical embodiment.</p>",
"8": "<p>YHWH's prohibition is stated with full solemnity: <span class='term'>dāmîm lārōḇ šāpaḵtā</span> — \"bloods in abundance you have shed.\" <span class='term'>dāmîm</span> (plural) denotes blood-guilt — not merely the physical act of killing but the weight of responsibility for multiple deaths. <span class='term'>milḥāmôt gᵉdōlôt ʿāśîtā</span> — \"you have waged great wars.\" The prohibition is not moral condemnation of David's wars per se (the Chronicler presents many of them as YHWH-commissioned) but a fitness-for-function judgment: the temple is a house of peace (<span class='term'>šālôm</span>), and its builder must embody that peace. War-making and temple-building require incompatible charisms.</p>",
"10": "<p><span class='term'>hûʾ yiḇneh bêt lišmî wᵉhûʾ yihyeh-lî lᵉḇēn wᵉʾănî lō lᵉʾāḇ</span> — the direct citation of 2 Sam 7:13–14 / the Davidic covenant. \"He will build a house for my name and he will be my son and I will be his father\" — the language of adoptive royal sonship from the Ancient Near Eastern treaty tradition where the great king describes his vassal-king as \"son.\" The Chronicler quotes the covenant verbatim within David's speech, making the temple-building mandate a matter of covenant fulfillment rather than merely royal ambition. Solomon builds not because David wants it but because YHWH promised it.</p>",
"11": "<p>David's blessing: <span class='term'>YHWH ʿimmāḵ wᵉhiṣlaḥtā ûḇānîtā bêt YHWH ʾĕlōhêḵā kaʾăšer dibber ʿālêḵā</span> — \"may YHWH be with you so that you succeed and build the house of the LORD your God as he has spoken concerning you.\" The conditional structure — YHWH's presence enables success — is the Chronicler's fundamental historical principle. Every successful building or battle in Chronicles succeeds because YHWH was with the protagonist; every failure occurs in his absence. David's blessing is both paternal affection and theological instruction.</p>",
"12": "<p><span class='term'>raq yittᵉn-lᵉḵā YHWH śēḵel ûḇînâ</span> — \"only may YHWH give you wisdom and understanding.\" <span class='term'>śēḵel</span> is practical wisdom/prudence; <span class='term'>ḇînâ</span> is discernment/insight. The paired terms echo Proverbs' wisdom vocabulary — the temple's construction requires the full complement of the wisdom tradition's intellectual virtues. The purpose clause — <span class='term'>wᵉlišmōr ʾet-tôrat YHWH ʾĕlōhêḵā</span> (\"to keep the torah of YHWH your God\") — makes wisdom instrumental to covenant faithfulness, not an end in itself. Solomon's later request for precisely this gift (2 Chr 1:10) fulfills David's blessing.</p>",
"13": "<p><span class='term'>ʾāz taṣlîaḥ ʾim-tišmōr laʿăśôt ʾet-haḥuqqîm wᵉʾet-hammišpāṭîm</span> — \"then you will succeed if you carefully observe the statutes and ordinances.\" The conditional <span class='term'>ʾāz/ʾim</span> structure (then/if) reflects Deuteronomic covenant logic: success is not guaranteed by hereditary right or building quality but by Torah faithfulness. <span class='term'>ḥăzaq wᵉʾĕmāṣ ʾal-tîrāʾ wᵉʾal-tēḥāt</span> — \"be strong and courageous, do not fear and do not be dismayed\" — the Joshua commission (Josh 1:6–9) applied to the temple-builder: the spiritual courage required to maintain Torah is as formidable as the courage required to conquer Canaan.</p>",
"14": "<p><span class='term'>bᵉʿonyî hăḵînôtî lᵉḇêt YHWH</span> — \"in my distress/affliction I have prepared for the house of the LORD.\" <span class='term'>ʿonî</span> (distress, affliction, poverty) is a surprising self-description from a king who is about to enumerate staggering resources; it acknowledges that David's wars, sins, and limitations are the context of his giving. The numbers are colossal: <span class='term'>mēʾâ ʾelep kkārim zāhāb</span> (100,000 talents of gold) / <span class='term'>ʾelep ʾălāpîm kkārê-kesef</span> (a million talents of silver) — whether literal or representing an incomprehensibly vast sum, the Chronicler makes clear that the temple received the accumulated wealth of David's campaigns, transformed from the instrument of war into the material of sacred space.</p>",
"15": "<p><span class='term'>ʿimmᵉḵā lārōḇ ʿōśê melāʾḵâ</span> — \"with you in abundance are those who do the work.\" David's inventory of craftsmen (stonecutters/masons/woodworkers/<span class='term'>ḵol-ḥākām-lēḇ bᵉḵol-melāʾḵâ</span> — \"every skilled-heart person in every craft\") echoes the Bezalel-and-Oholiab assembly for the tabernacle (Exod 31:6; 36:1–2). The phrase <span class='term'>ḥākām-lēḇ</span> (skilled/wise of heart) is the Exodus vocabulary for craftsmen whose skill is divinely given — David frames the temple workforce in tabernacle terms, establishing the spiritual continuity between Moses' wilderness tent and Solomon's permanent house.</p>",
"16": "<p><span class='term'>zāhāḇ kesef wᵉnᵉḥōšet ûḇarzel ʾên mispār</span> — \"gold, silver, bronze, and iron beyond counting.\" The fourfold metal formula (gold/silver/bronze/iron) reflects the descending scale of cultic and material value from the innermost sanctuary (gold) to the outer structure (iron). <span class='term'>qûm wᵃʿăśēh wîhî YHWH ʿimmāḵ</span> — \"rise and do it, and may YHWH be with you.\" The imperative charge is brief and absolute: all preparation is complete, divine presence is invoked, the command is given. David's last word to Solomon on the temple is not another exhortation but a departure — he entrusts the work.</p>",
"17": "<p>David extends the temple charge to all Israel's leaders: <span class='term'>wayyṣaw dāwîd lᵉḵol-śārê yiśrāʾēl laʿzōr lišlōmōh bᵉnô</span> — \"David commanded all the leaders of Israel to support his son Solomon.\" The royal succession is presented as a community project rather than a dynastic transfer: the leaders are not merely informed of the succession but commissioned to actively support the new king in the temple project. This democratic dimension of the Chronicles theology — shared communal investment in the sacred project — will climax in 1 Chr 29's freewill-offering assembly.</p>",
"18": "<p>The rhetorical questions construct Israel's covenant security as the basis for action: <span class='term'>hălōʾ YHWH ʾĕlōhêkem ʿimmāḵem</span> (\"Is not YHWH your God with you?\") / <span class='term'>ûheniḥ lāḵem missāḇîḇ</span> (\"Has he not given you rest on every side?\") — the <span class='term'>mᵉnûḥâ</span> (rest) from enemies is both the political precondition for temple-building and the theological meaning of Solomon's reign (22:9). <span class='term'>nātan bᵉyāḏî ʾet-yōšᵉḇê hāʾāreṣ</span> — YHWH has already given the land's inhabitants into David's hand; the military work is done. What remains is the sacred work.</p>",
"19": "<p>The climactic charge: <span class='term'>ûttᵉnû lᵉḇaḇḵem wᵉnapšᵉḵem liḏrōš lYHWH ʾĕlōhêḵem</span> — \"give your heart and soul to seeking YHWH your God.\" <span class='term'>lēḇāḇ</span> (heart, will, intellect) + <span class='term'>nepeš</span> (soul, life force) — the total-person dedication formula (Deut 6:5; 30:6) applied to the temple enterprise. <span class='term'>qûmû ûḇᵉnû ʾet-miqdaš YHWH</span> — \"rise and build the sanctuary of YHWH\" — the final imperative uses <span class='term'>miqdāš</span> (holy place, sanctuary) rather than <span class='term'>bêt</span> (house), shifting from architectural to sacred register. Bringing the ark and holy vessels into the sanctuary is the goal: not architecture for its own sake but the dwelling-place of YHWH's name among his people.</p>",
},
}

